ğŸ” Version 1 â€” Basic Slideshow (Infinite Loop, Simple)
This is a pretty standard manual slideshow â€” youâ€™re just sliding the ul left or
right using animate(). When you hit the end, the counter loops back to 0.

Key Things
âœ… On next click, counter++ moves you forward.
âœ… On previous click, counter-- moves you back.
âœ… If counter gets too high (at the end), it resets to 0 (first image).
âœ… If counter goes negative (at the beginning), it wraps to the last image.

Animation

- $('#slider ul').animate({left: leftPosition}, 700, 'easeInQuad');
- Moves the whole image strip to the correct spot.
- easeInQuad is a fancy easing animation (slows in smoothly).
  Simple, but no cloning. Just shifts and loops.

---

ğŸ” Version 2 â€” Fancy Cloning Version (Seamless Looping)
This one is more advanced â€” it creates a clone of the ul at the end or start so the animation feels smoother and can wrap seamlessly.

Key Differences
âœ… When you hit the last image (counter === imageCount), it:

- Clones the ul
- Appends the clone to #slider
- Puts the new ul just off-screen to the right.
- Slides the new ul into place.
- Slides the old ul off the screen.
- Deletes the old ul.
  âœ… The same logic applies when moving backwards from the first slide â€” it clones the ul and puts it off-screen to the left.

Why Clone?
This avoids a â€œjumpâ€ effect when the slideshow resets. Instead of snapping back to the first slide, it looks like it keeps sliding smoothly. Much more pro-looking.

